byline.original: By NELSON BRYANTSpecial to The New York Times

results.lead_paragraph: LANDER, Wyo. -- Dawn was cold 7,500 feet high in the foothills of Wyoming's Wind River Mountains. But the sky was clear and when the Indian Summer sun rose its warmth touched the cottonwoods in the valleys and gleamed on the yellowing leaves of the aspens on the hillsides as we looked down into South Pass, a portion of the Oregon Trail that cuts through the mountains at this point.

headline.main: Ellington Giving Music Collection to Yale

results.snippet: Duke Ellington plans to give his collection of original compositions and arrangements to Yale University for its James Weldon Johnson Collection of Negro Arts and Letters. Announcement of the gift was made in New Haven by Willie Ruff, an associate...
results.lead_paragraph: Duke Ellington plans to give his collection of original compositions and arrangements to Yale University for its James Weldon Johnson Collection of Negro Arts and Letters. Announcement of the gift was made in New Haven by Willie Ruff, an associate professor of music. The Ellington collection includes letters and manuscripts from black writers and composers of the 19th and 20th centuries.

results.abstract: NASA spokesman on Oct 3 discloses that 179-yr-old US coin, secreted on Gemini 7 spacecraft in '65, was sold recently for $15,000 to Fla coin dealer W F Steinberg; contends no one connected with NASA, including Gemini 7 astronauts Col F Borman and Capt J A Lovell Jr, profited from transaction; says coin was placed in in-flight med kit by flight surgeon Dr H Minners; notes coin was property of Minneapolis coin dealer W Ulrich; says Minners, Borman and Lovell signed lr certifying that coin had been in space and then returned it to Ulrich, who sold coin to Steinberg 2 mos ago; Steinberg maintains coin could now be worth $100,000

headline.main: Coin, Once in Orbit, Sells for $15,000

results.snippet: HOUSTON, Oct. 4 (AP) -- A 179-year-old United States coin, which was secreted on board the Gemini 7 spacecraft in 1965, was sold recently for $15,000, and the man who sold it said it could now be worth as much as $100,000.

headline.main: Apollo 17 Geologist Looks Forward to Moon Sampling

results.snippet: WASHINGTON, Oct. 27 -- The geologist-astronaut who will go to the moon on Apollo 17 said today there was "a good chance" that the mission would uncover both some of the youngest and some of the oldest lunar rocks ever examined by man.
